value.value: One of the veins draining a meninix.
Accompanying vein of internal pudendal artery.
One of the veins of the pelvis which drain into the great saphenous vein.
A branch of the superior mesenteric artery that supplies the jejunum.
A vein that drains a lacrimal gland.
Any portion of submucosa that lines the digestive tract.
Any organ component layer that consists of muscle tissue.
A muscular coat that is part of a digestive tract.

label.value: dorsal zone of medial entorhinal cortex
ventral zone of medial entorhinal cortex

value.value: The dorsal region of the lateral ganglionic eminence. The cells in this area give rise to embryonic interneuron precursors that will migrate tangentially to the olfactory bulb.

The anterior or rostral end of the zygomatic arch, which includes the temporal process of the zygomatic bone, but also including some of the body of the zygomatic bone. It may also include the zygomatico-temporal suture and the most rostral portion of the zygomatic process of the temporal bone.
The third phalangeal bone in a digit ray.
Foramen housing the root of the spinal nerve seen in the neural arch of the first vertebrae (atlas). (see Edwards 1976).
Adrenal tissue dispersed in clusters, found in periphery and center of adrenal gland in turtles (Yadav, 2008).

Adrenal tissue aggregated in a dorsal layer covering internal cords, found in lepidosaur adrenal glands. Islets of adrenal tissue found on ventral surface of gland (barely present in squamates). See Yadav, 2008.
Adrenal tissue found in archosaurs - tissue arranged in bands, alternating with interrenal cords (Yadav, 2008).
In mammals, adrenal tissue has a cortex and medulla creating a composite adrenal gland (Kardong 2012).
The highest elevation of the paracone on a molariform tooth.
The anterior region of the maxillary tooth row, if that tooth row contains teeth that are substantially over the premaxillary teeth (see Laurin and Reisz 1995).
A postcingulum found on deciduous premolar 5.
A posthypocrista found on deciduous premolar 5.
A protuberence or true tooth that is used during hatching to break the eggshell.
Tooth used to break the eggshell, that is shed soon after hatching. In lepidosaurs, a true tooth that is shed soon after hatching.
Epidermal outgrowth that facilitates breaking of the eggshell in archosaurs and monotremes.
The labial most of three cusps on the talonoid (posterior) end of lower molariform teeth. (modified from http://animaldiversity.ummz.umich.edu/collections/mammal_anatomy/cheek_teeth_structure/).
Fifth premolar (counting anteroposteriorly ) in the lower jaw.
Third molar (counting anteroposteriorly) in the lower jaw.
Pharyngeal toothplate of the lower jaw region; typically associated with ceratobranchial 5 element.
First premolar (counting anteroposteriorly ) in the lower jaw.
Second premolar (counting anteroposteriorly ) in the lower jaw.
Posteroloph found on the first molar tooth.
Hypoconid found on the first premolar tooth.
The anterior cusp along the labial margin seen in the molar or premolar teeth of mammals. (modified from http://animaldiversity.ummz.umich.edu/collections/mammal_anatomy/cheek_teeth_structure/).
A crest running along the labial margin of molarifomr teeth of mammals. (modified from http://animaldiversity.ummz.umich.edu/collections/mammal_anatomy/cheek_teeth_structure/).
A shelf like ridge on the posterior (distal) outside edge of the upper molariform teeth. (modified from http://animaldiversity.ummz.umich.edu/collections/mammal_anatomy/cheek_teeth_structure/).
A shelf like ridge on the outside of the upper molariform teeth. (modified from http://animaldiversity.ummz.umich.edu/collections/mammal_anatomy/cheek_teeth_structure/).
A crest on the hypoconid of molariform teeth. (modified from http://animaldiversity.ummz.umich.edu/collections/mammal_anatomy/cheek_teeth_structure/).
A shelf like ridge on the proximal (mesial) outside edge of the upper molariform teeth. (modified from http://animaldiversity.ummz.umich.edu/collections/mammal_anatomy/cheek_teeth_structure/).
First premolar (counting anteroposteriorly) in the jaw.
An enamel ridge joining the protocone and the paracone on the occlusal surface of a maxillary molar.
Tooth (often obscured from view) in a 'waiting' position that will replace an existing tooth (i.e. a tooth that is well visible in the jaw).
A pit formed in an existing functional tooth, causing resorption of the surrounding dentine and periodontal tissues. (modified from LeBlanc and Reisz 2013, see figures 8, 10 for more details).
Cusp found on a platform that is buccaal and mesial to the meta and paracones. Modified from Kermack 1967. Molar evolution in Mesozoic mammals.
Tooth of the lower jaw that is adjacent to the mandibular symphysis.
First canine (counting anteroposteriorly) in the upper jaw.
Fifth premolar (counting anteroposteriorly ) in the upper jaw.
First molar (counting anteroposteriorly) in the upper jaw.
